In response to high white evangelical support for Donald Trump and the Republican Party,[268] Hillary Scholten, a member of the Christian Reformed Church, founded the Christian Democrats of America.[269][undue weight?  – discuss] During the 2020 primaries, Christians were more likely to support Joe Biden than Bernie Sanders, who was favored among religiously unaffiliated Democrats.[270] 1,600 faith leaders (mostly mainline Protestants, evangelicals, and Catholics) supported Joe Biden's 2020 presidential bid.[271][undue weight?  – discuss] Robb Ryerse, political director at Vote Common Good, a religiously-motivated anti-Trump organization, estimated that there were roughly a dozen evangelical Christians running for political office as Democrats in 2020, as opposed to two or three in 2018.[269][undue weight?  – discuss]
